Basic commands for the user:

| Command |     What it Does                     |           Example                |
|---------|--------------------------------------|----------------------------------|
| pwd     |   Shows current directory            | `pwd` â†’ `/home/user`             |
| uname -a|   Shows system information           | `uname -a`                       |
| whoami  |   Shows current logged-in user       | `whoami`                         |
| clear   |   Clears the terminal screen         | `clear`                          |
| history |   Shows previously used commands     | `history`                        |



Directory commands:

| Command    |     What it Does                     |           Example                |
|------------|--------------------------------------|----------------------------------|
| ls         |   Lists files and folders            | `ls`                             |
| ls -a      |   Shows hidden files                 | `ls -a`                          |
| cd         |   Change directory                   | `cd myfolder`                    |
| cd ..      |   Move one directory up              | `cd ..`                          |
| cd ../..   |   Move two directories up            | `cd ../..`                       |
| cd -       |   Go to previous directory           | `cd -`                           |
| mkdir      |   Create a new directory             | `mkdir project`                  |
| mkdir -p   |   Create nested directories          | `mkdir -p a/b/c`                 |



File commands:

| Command    |     What it Does                     |           Example                |
|------------|--------------------------------------|----------------------------------|
| touch      |   Create an empty file               | `touch file.txt`                 |
| cp         |   Copy a file                        | `cp a.txt b.txt`                 |
| mv         |   Rename or move a file              | `mv old.txt new.txt`             |
| rm         |   Delete a file                      | `rm file.txt`                    |
| rm *.txt   |   Delete all .txt files              | `rm *.txt`                       |
| rm *       |   Delete all files (dangerous)       | Use carefully                    |
| cat        |   Display file contents              | `cat file.txt`                   |
| echo       |   Display text                       | `echo "Hello"`                   |
| echo >>    |   Append text to a file              | `echo "Hi" >> file.txt`          |



text editor: 

| Editor |     What it Does                     |           Example                |
|--------|--------------------------------------|----------------------------------|
| vi     |   Open Vi editor                     | `vi file.txt`                    |
| vim    |   Open Vim editor                    | `vim file.txt`                   |
| nano   |   Simple text editor                 | `nano file.txt`                  |



Editor shortcuts:

| Shortcut |     What it Does                     |
|----------|--------------------------------------|
| :q!      |   Quit vi/vim without saving         |
| dd       |   Delete a line in vi/vim             |
| Ctrl + X |   Exit Nano editor                   |
| Ctrl + Y |   Save file in Nano                  |



Useful shortcuts:

| Shortcut         |     What it Does                     |
|------------------|--------------------------------------|
| Tab              |   Auto-complete command or file       |
| Ctrl + Shift + C |   Copy from terminal                 |
| Ctrl + Shift + V |   Paste into terminal                |

